# Documentation and decision records

- Code should explain what it does through structure, naming, types, and narrow interfaces.
- Comments MUST explain why, constraints, invariants, non-obvious tradeoffs, safety assumptions, or performance reasoning. NEVER narrate obvious syntax.
- Performance-critical functions MUST include a concise complexity note: time, auxiliary space, dominant allocation/copy behavior, and important worst-case inputs.
- Public interfaces MUST document contract, errors, side effects, idempotency, thread/concurrency behavior, and compatibility guarantees.
- Material architectural decisions require an ADR using `docs/engineering/adr-template.md`.
- Security-sensitive changes require a threat model or delta using `docs/engineering/threat-model-template.md`.
- New critical operations require runbook and observability updates.
- Documentation MUST describe current verified behavior. NEVER describe planned controls as implemented.
- Examples MUST compile or be tested when practical and MUST not contain real credentials or sensitive production data.
